**Explanation:** A debouncer in JavaScript delays invoking a function until after a certain amount of time has elapsed since the last time the debounced function was invoked.

**Code:**

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function (...args) {
    const context = this;
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(context, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage:
const heavyFunction = () => {
  console.log('Heavy Computation...');
};

const debouncedFunction = debounce(heavyFunction, 300);

debouncedFunction(); // Call it once
debouncedFunction(); // Call it again within 300ms
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log('This will print now, as 300ms have passed since the last call');
}, 350);
```

In this example, `heavyFunction` will only be called after each 300ms interval, even if it's invoked multiple times within that window. This technique is useful for preventing excessive, frequent invocations of resource-intensive functions, like API calls or DOM manipulations.
